## Step-by-step Deobfuscation

The code uses a common obfuscation pattern: a string array (`a0_0x469c`) with base64-encoded strings, a decoder function (`a0_0x4c68`), and a shuffling IIFE to arrange the string array correctly. Let me decode it all.

## Deobfuscated Code

```javascript
const TWO_PI = Math.PI * 2;

const CONFIG = {
  repulsionK: 4000,       // Repulsion force constant
  springK: 0.004,         // Default spring stiffness
  damping: 0.92,          // Velocity damping factor
  gravity: 0.0003,        // Gravity toward center (400, 300)
  particleMax: 40,        // Max number of particles
  particleFade: 0.04,     // (declared but not heavily used in this snippet)
  cameraEase: 0.06        // Camera easing/lerp speed
};

// === NODES (graph vertices) ===
const nodes = [
  { id: "central", label: "Hub",      r: 26, x: 400, y: 300, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "alpha",   label: "Alpha",    r: 16, x: 500, y: 200, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "beta",    label: "Beta",     r: 16, x: 300, y: 400, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "gamma",   label: "Gamma",    r: 14, x: 250, y: 180, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "delta",   label: "Delta",    r: 14, x: 550, y: 380, vx: 0, vy: 0 },
  { id: "epsilon", label: "Epsilon",  r: 12, x: 350, y: 150, vx: 0, vy: 0 }
];

// === EDGES (springs connecting nodes) ===
const edges = [
  { a: "central", b: "alpha",   rest: 160, k: 0.006 },
  { a: "central", b: "beta",    rest: 160, k: 0.005 },
  { a: "central", b: "gamma",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "central", b: "delta",   rest: 170, k: 0.004 },
  { a: "central", b: "epsilon", rest: 180, k: 0.003 },
  { a: "alpha",   b: "beta",    rest: 200, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "gamma",   b: "delta",   rest: 220, k: 0.002 },
  { a: "alpha",   b: "epsilon", rest: 200, k: 0.002 }
];

// === CAMERA ===
let camera       = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };
let cameraTarget  = { x: 400, y: 300, zoom: 1 };

// === PARTICLES ===
let particles = [];
let frameCount = 0;

// Helper: find node by ID
function findNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}

// === PHYSICS STEP ===
function physicsStep() {
  // 1) Node-node REPULSION (Coulomb-like)
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      let dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      let dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      let dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
      let force = CONFIG.repulsionK / (dist * dist);
      let fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      let fy = (dy / dist) * force;
      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // 2) Edge SPRING forces (Hooke's law)
  for (let i = 0; i < edges.length; i++) {
    let nodeA = findNode(edges[i].a);
    let nodeB = findNode(edges[i].b);
    if (!nodeA || !nodeB) continue;
    let dx = nodeB.x - nodeA.x;
    let dy = nodeB.y - nodeA.y;
    let dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;
    let displacement = dist - edges[i].rest;
    let force = (edges[i].k || CONFIG.springK) * displacement;
    nodeA.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeA.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    nodeB.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // 3) Apply damping, centering gravity, and integrate position
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    nodes[i].vx += (400 - nodes[i].x) * CONFIG.gravity;  // gravity toward center X
    nodes[i].vy += (300 - nodes[i].y) * CONFIG.gravity;  // gravity toward center Y
    nodes[i].vx *= CONFIG.damping;
    nodes[i].vy *= CONFIG.damping;
    nodes[i].x += nodes[i].vx;
    nodes[i].y += nodes[i].vy;
  }
}

// === SPAWN PARTICLE ===
function spawnParticle() {
  if (particles.length >= CONFIG.particleMax) return;
  let node = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  let angle = Math.random() * TWO_PI;
  let speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * 0.7;
  particles.push({
    x: node.x,
    y: node.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + Math.random() * 1.2
  });
}

// === UPDATE PARTICLES ===
function updateParticles() {
  for (let i = particles.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    let p = particles[i];
    p.vx *= 0.995;   // slight drag
    p.vy *= 0.995;
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;
    p.age++;
    if (p.age > p.maxAge) particles.splice(i, 1);
  }
}

// === UPDATE CAMERA (smooth easing) ===
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * CONFIG.cameraEase;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * CONFIG.cameraEase;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * CONFIG.cameraEase;
}

// === MAIN TICK ===
function tick() {
  updateCamera();       // smooth camera
  physicsStep();        // run force simulation
  updateParticles();    // move & cull particles
  if (frameCount % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();  // spawn every 3rd frame
  frameCount++;
}

setInterval(tick, 16);  // ~60 FPS
```

## What It Does

This is a **force-directed graph simulation** — the same kind of physics used in tools like D3.js force layouts. Specifically:

### 🔵 Graph Structure
- **6 nodes** ("Hub", "Alpha", "Beta", "Gamma", "Delta", "Epsilon") connected by **8 edges/springs**
- "Hub" (central) connects to all others; some peripheral nodes connect to each other

### ⚛️ Physics Engine
1. **Repulsion** — All node pairs repel each other (inverse-square law, like charged particles)
2. **Spring attraction** — Connected nodes are pulled together by Hooke's law springs with configurable rest lengths and stiffness
3. **Centering gravity** — Weak force pulls everything toward (400, 300)
4. **Velocity damping** (0.92) — Prevents runaway oscillation

### ✨ Particle System
- Every 3 frames, a decorative particle spawns at a random node, drifts outward with slight drag, and dies after 800–2000 frames — purely cosmetic ambient effect

### 🎥 Camera
- Smoothly eases toward a target position/zoom using linear interpolation (though the target never changes in this code, suggesting external code would update `cameraTarget`)

### Summary
> **It's the simulation backend for an animated, interactive node-graph visualization** — the kind you'd see as a network diagram with nodes gently floating, connected by elastic links, with sparkle particles drifting around. The rendering/drawing code is not included here — this is purely the physics and state update loop running at ~60 FPS.
